<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-05-04T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-05-04T05:00:00-05:00" n="940" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d940">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 855.48/588</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_WJE1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Willard</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Madrid</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-05-04T10:00:00+00:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">May 4, 1917, 10 a.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                                <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 10.15 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>520. Department’s 328, March 6 [<hi rend="italic">16?</hi>], 4 p.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d940fn1">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_652">p.
                                652</ref>.</note> German Minister for Foreign Affairs states that if
                                <hi rend="italic">Storstad</hi> was sunk in war zone on March 8 it
                            was fault of captain who was at Saint Vincent from February 6 until end
                            of month and, therefore, must have known of declaration of war zone and
                            nevertheless ventured to enter it. Also states that so far as known ship
                            was not provided with German safe-conduct in which case vessel showed
                            without right the characteristics of the insignia of Commission for
                            Relief of Belgians.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_WJE1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Willard</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>